We call on our colleagues to put aside the headline-grabbing rhetoric, look at the data that should drive our policy decision-making, and move forward with passing a strong, pro-safety bill to reauthorize the FAA.

Our amendment does NOT:
❌Reduce the the agreed-upon standard of 1,500 hours of training time
❌Allow untrained, unskilled pilots to operate aircrafts

Here’s what our amendment does:
✅Allows the FAA to evaluate training technologies like flight simulations
✅Ensures the FAA has authority over pilot training, only changing training requirements if changes are proven to enhance aviation safety
✅Diversifies the pilot pipeline

That’s why @SenJohnThune and I are proposing an amendment to the reauthorization legislation that requires the FAA to establish a comprehensive curriculum to make pilot training more effective and enhance the safety of our skies.

When Congress reauthorizes a governmental agency, it should identify ways to make government work better for the public. With increasing delays, cancellations, and an alarming number of near-miss events, the time to ensure our pilots remain the most qualified in the world is now.

ICYMI: As we work to reauthorize the Federal Aviation Administration, @SenJohnThune and I know there are commonsense ways to address challenges facing our aviation system while ensuring the highest safety standards for passengers. 🧵

HEAT STROKE

Signs: Extremely high body temperature (above 103 degrees), hot and dry skin with no sweat, rapid pulse, confusion, or unconsciousness.

Actions: Call 911 or get the person to a hospital immediately. Cool down with whatever methods are available until help arrives.

HEAT EXHAUSTION:

Signs: Heavy sweating, paleness, muscle cramps, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, or fainting.

Actions: Lie down in an air-conditioned or shaded area. Loosen clothing. Take sips of cool sports drinks with salt and sugar. Get medical help if symptoms get worse.

HEAT CRAMPS:

Signs: Muscle pains or spasms in the stomach, arms, or legs.

Actions: Go to a cooler location, remove excess clothing, take sips of cool sports drinks with salt and sugar. Get medical help if cramps last more than an hour.
